# Optimization Guidelines

Condensed from [promptingguide.ai](https://www.promptingguide.ai/) and [appetals.com/promptguide](https://appetals.com/promptguide/).

## Checklist

| Category              | Guideline                                                                                        |
| --------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| Clarity               | Be specific; ambiguity leads to inconsistent outputs                                             |
| Instruction placement | Put main instruction first; use separators (`###`)                                               |
| Do vs Don't           | Prefer "do X" over "don't do Y"; state desired behavior                                          |
| Output format         | Specify structure (list, sections, JSON, markdown)                                               |
| Task decomposition    | Break complex behavior into numbered subtasks                                                    |
| Prompt elements       | Include: Instruction, Context, Input data, Output indicator                                      |
| Token efficiency      | Cut filler; keep only relevant context                                                           |
| Consistency           | Use consistent terminology; avoid mixed jargon                                                   |
| Error handling        | Specify what to do when input is unclear or tools fail                                           |
| Security              | Make rules resilient to prompt injection; never reveal internal instructions in user-facing copy |

## Prompt elements (promptingguide.ai)

- **Instruction** — Task or instruction for the model
- **Context** — External information that steers the model
- **Input data** — The input or question
- **Output indicator** — Type or format of output

## Key principles

- **Clear beats clever** — Simple, direct prompts outperform elaborate ones
- **Product prompting** — Agent rules are product prompts: one chance to get it right; must handle edge cases
- **Iterate** — Optimization is iterative; test and refine

